item.title: Introduction
item.description:
[Lecture on 1.1]
Lecture "1.1" refers to week 1, day 1 (i.e. Monday). Similar notation is used throughout

Professor: Mark Flanagan
N.B. Module content has changed since last year, previous exams may not be relevant

Necessary backgrounds:

Signals & System (Fourier, FFT, autocorrelation, PSD, etc.)
Probability Theory (Bayes' rule)
Random Signals (AWGN, etc.)
Linear Algebra (Vector spaces, inner products, etc.)
Preliminary section on DMCs and MAP rule.
Three mains sections:

Signal space analysis
Modulation techniques
Wireless communications
Recommended textbook: "Communication Systems" by Simon Haykin (4th ed)



Idealised channel with no memory.
Symbols can be sent. Symbols can be received. Transmitter must identify sent symbols based on the received symbols.

A matrix maps the probability of each TX symbol being received as each RX symbols
'a priori' probabilities give the probability of being sent in the first place
'a posteriori' probabilities give the probability that was sent based on

Question: Suppose is observed at the output. What is the optimum decision rule?
Answer: Want to be the most likely value could have had based on the observation i.e. we want to choose to maximise . This is called the "maximum a posteriori" (MAP) rule.

[End of lecture on 1.1]
[Lecture on 1.3]

Here the receiver sets its decision to the symbol for which was the most likely to be received, i.e.

Note: People often misuse the term 'maximum likelihood' to refer to MAP (though this is often irrelevant because values are usually equiprobable)

[End of lecture on 1.3]
[Lecture on 1.4]

If the a priori probabilities are unknown, we treat them as variables and consider the worst-case set of a priori probabilities for each possible rule, then select the rule with the lowest worst-case probability of error.
Consider a BSC with 0s and 1s - let the a priori probability of 0 be denoted P(0).
There are four possible decision rules - plot the probability of error for each one as a function of P(0). You'll find it's a set of lines in the box [0,0]-[1,1]
The minimax rule is the one with the lowest maximum.

item.description:
[Lecture on 1.4]

Information Theory COMP 30690
Flix Balado
Each class is a 50 minute lecture, then a 50 minute tutorial
TA: Malick Ebiele (mossoun.ebiele@ucdconnect.ie)
Contact TA first re. assignment corrections
Tutorials run by Prof, TA just does assignment grading
Lectures not recorded

Two assignments (15% each)
Indicatives dates are posted
Two weeks to complete them after they are posted
Assignment 1: Posted in week 6, due in week 8
Assignment 2: Posted in week 11, due in week 13
Late submissions:

10 percentage points will be deducted during the first week late
20 percentage points will be deducted during the second week late
Final Exam

70% mark
Closed-book
5/6 short questions similar to those seen in tutorials & assignments
Nonprogrammable calculators allowed
Linear grading scale
Calculation points scheme with three components (2 assignments and a final exam)


Submit only through Brightspace
Handwriting is not acceptable (except original hand-drawn figures)
Must be searchable PDF format
If programming is required, your original source code must be submitted
Include explicit instructions (README file) on how to run/compile it
Submit separate files separately, no zip files
The plagiarism detector won't work on zip files (lmao good to know)
Any programming language is fine (he will be using MATLAB)


Introduction and Prerequesites
Review of calculus and algebra
Entropy, mutual information, asymptotic equipartition property...
Data compression
Error detection and correction
Channel capacity

Mainly:

T. Cover & J. Thomas "Elements of Information Theory" (2nd ed.) Wiley & Sons 2006 (Chapters 1,2,3,5,7)
Also:

S. Ross "A First Course on Probability" (10th ed.) Prentice Hall, 2018
D. McKay "Information Theory, Inference, and Learning Algorithms" Cambridge University Press, 2004

Claude Shannon developed the theory of information during WWII (wasn't published till after the war)
Seminal paper: A mathematical theory of communication
According to Shannon
Information Information is the ability to distinguish reliably among possible alternative messages
i.e. one of many possibilities is being encoded
There is a greater than 95% chance of at least 1 bit error occurring in 4 GB of memory in a 72h period at sea level - error detection and correction is important!
Most basic error correction scheme:

Send every symbol three times and take the majority
This is reasonably effective but not at all foolproof, and extremely inefficient
Every noisy channel has a 'capacity' (C) which defines the limit on the 'rate' of code (i.e. the ratio of original message to encoded message)
(C is dimensionless, not bits/second, confusing name though right?)m

item.title: Module Overview
item.description:
[Lecture on 1.3]

Professor John Murphy
j.murphy@ucd.ie
You are expected to attend all lectures - they are not recorded and there will be important information not included in the emails.

"Computer Networks, 5th ed"
Prentice Hall 2010
Andrew S. Tanenbaum and Wetherall
Entirely optional - notes should be sufficient.

Problem sets will be given out
They are not graded or handed up, they're practice

Four in-class tests
Provisional dates:
Test 1: Friday October 4th (11 am) 10% (Week 4)
Test 2: Friday October 25th (11 am) 20% (Week 7)
Test 3: Friday November 15th (11 am) 30% (Week 10)
Final Exam (on-campus with laptop) in the exam period - 40%
We'll get letter grades for each one (I think ?) then he uses the calculation points system for final grades.


Two extreme topologies:
Mesh vs. central

Mesh obviously requires way too many links
Central has drawbacks:

Single point of failure (router)
Single link failure cuts off a node
Enormous traffic at router node
Potentially wasteful if lots of communications are to 'nearby' devices
So we'll need something inbetween

So what is the optimum number of switches?
Limit on scale of a single switch.
Reliability of a single switch is also limited.
Two kinds of link:

User to switch ('access link')
Switch to switch
You get topologies that could look like this:

Example
In Ireland there are 5 million phones
Connected by about 10k mobile masts
These are connected by ~100 major switches
So
500 phones per mast
50,000 phones per major switch
Switches connected through a backbone network (backbone could be as few as 5-6 massive switches)


How to measure performance?
Cost to build switch
Number of inputs/outputs
Can all possible connections be switched?
How does the switch grow with connection count
Functionality and technology of the switch (not on this module)


Device that can connect any of n inputs to any of m outputs
Provided the output is not busy
1-1 connections only
This is called a 'strictly non-blocking switch'
i.e. any connection can be made (if they're free), so it should never block a connection




Weaker alternatives to strictly non-blocking switch
Non-blocking with Rearrangement:
Allows any connection to be made, but may require other existing connections be rearranged
Non-Blocking with Connection Packing Rule
Non-blocking as long as the connections are put up in a particular order
Some blocking may be acceptable if it's small enough.


Switching gets much more difficult with scale - we'll look at generally 1000 ports
Input/output is a bit of an abstract idea, in reality they are usually one and the same
Crosspoint: connects an input to an output.
We often want to minimise how many we need as they may be expensive
Basic analogue crosspoint:

Crossbar Switch
Each crosspoint here can be enabled to link the two wires passing under it Consider that this switch has 512 possible configurations, the vast majority of which are not very useful. This may suggest that there are too many crosspoints ( crosspoints)
Modern crosspoints are electronic transistors
See also: Time Switching
[End of lecture on 1.3]
[Lecture on 1.5]


Usually we will look at square switches (equal inputs and output)
Want to minimise the number of crosspoints C() as each one has an associated cost
Multi-stage switches are one option
Clos Networks are the key idea

Clos Networks
Three stage switch

Notice the switches on the right have transposed dimensions from the ones on the left
sometimes
Strictly non-blocking

input switches (each is an -> crossbar)
center switches (each is -> crossbar)
output switches (each is a -> crossbar)
You can apply this idea recursively, turning the center stage (of crossbars) into its own Clos network
Number of crosspoints:

Input stage:
Output stage: Same again
Center stage:
Noting that , you get
Total:
Optimal value is and giving
For , this beats a crossbar.
You'll need to round up or down to an integer usually - generally you should attempt both up and down and see which performs better.

Calculate and round it up, then calculate and always round that up (so you have enough ports)
Then try again but round down

The middle stage has the most switches, so we can eliminate some by replacing that with a 3-stage clos switch, yielding a 5-stage switch.

There is an optimal number of stages for a given value of N
Generally you'll only need 3 or 5 stages, it's only worth implementing more for extremely large switches
See also: Networks and Internet Systems > Recursion

Java Textbook:

Core Java, Volume 1: Fundamentals 1 (Cay Horstmann) (Addison-Wesley Professional, 12th ed.)
Software Engineering Textbook:

Software Engineering (Ian Sommerville) Pearson, 10th ed
Recommends not bothering with the Java one, you can learn Java from the slides or online, but the software engineering textbook is good.


Why Java?
Getting started
Hello World
Data Types
Operators
Strings
I/O
Control Flow
Arrays

Java White Paper:

Simple, Object-Oriented and Familiar
Robust & secure
Architecture neutral and portable
High performance
Interpreted, threaded, and dynamic
Faster development cycle, less compiling and shite
Constant garbage collection for good memory management
Multithreading is basked into Java programs
Maintains the OOP nature of C++ but more secure, robust, convenient

C/C++ is compiled to 'native code' which cannot be ported between machines
Java executable (.jar) runs on any machine via a virtual machine
Java compiles to 'bytecode' (.jar file)
Java is highly employable

Download and install the latest Java SDK. Easiest to use the installer.
Download and install IntelliJ (IDE)

/* Multiline comments like this @author Thomas O'Dea @version 1.0 09-09-2024 Those lines are 'JavaDoc' notation */ public class HelloWorld { public static void main(String[] args) { System.out.println("Hello, World"); // Print } } Copy

First we declare a class (everything needs a class)
Then declare a method
- Our main method gets String[] args from CLI
Then instructions, semicolon delimited
- 'system' is a built-in class of Java
There should be one class in a source (text) file, and the file should have the same name with .java (HelloWorld.java) always capitalised

Java will automatically cast an int to a String if passed into a String argument
e.g. "Your balance is " + balance + " euros".
Integers:

int (4 bytes)
short (2 bytes)
long (8 bytes)
byte (1 byte)
Also:

char
double
boolean
Variables can be inferred implicitly, e.g.
var stage = 1;
Constants are declared with the 'final' keyword. Convention is that their names be all uppercase with underscores.
enum types are useful:
enum Grade {A, B, C, D, FAIL}; Grade studentGrade = Grade.B; System.out.println("Your grade is "+studentGrade) // Implicit string casting will take the enumerated name here! cool Copy
[Lecture on 1.4]

The 'math' class contains useful methods for arithmetic (e.g. Math.sqrt(x))
Doubles can be cast to int e.g.
double ySqrt = Math.sqrt(y); int ySqrtInt = (int) ySqrt; Copy
Behaviour is truncation
Standard incrementors i++; i--; ++i; --i;
Ternary operator: condition ? iftrue ? else
if A and B uses short-circuit logic

String firstName = "Thomas"; String concatenated = firstName +" " + firstName; firstName.repeat(3); firstName.substring(0,3); firstname.equals("Thomas"); // Returns true firstName.equalsIgnoreCase("thomas")' // Returns true firstName.length(); Copy


Need to import 'Scanner' package
import java.util.Scanner; // you can also just import all of util with import java.util.*; Copy
Create a scanner object and use it:
Scanner in = new Scanner(System.in); String rawInput = in.nextLine(); String rawNumberInput = in.nextInt(); Copy

import java.util.*; public class FormattedNumber { public static void main(String[] args) { double numberIncorrectCast = 100/3; // This calculates as integers, then casts, so you get 33.0 double numberCorrectCast = 100.0/3.0; // This is correct System.out.printf("Compare %8.2f %8.2f\n", numberIncorrectCast, numberCorrectCast); String name = "Thomas"; char letter = 'j'; boolean fact = true; int age = 18; System.out.printf("Details: %s %c %b %d\n", name, letter, fact, age); } } Copy

import java.util.*; import java.io.*; public class CopyFile { public static void main(String[] args) throws FileNotFoundException { // Create i/o objects for each file Scanner in = new Scanner(new File("fileInput.txt")); PrintWriter out = new PrintWriter("fileOutput.txt"); String inputData; while (in.hasNextLine()) { // ^ this prevents it reading beyond the file's end inputData = in.nextLine(); out.println(inputData); } // files must be closed in.close(); out.close(); } } Copy

[End of lecture 1.4]
[Lecture on 2.1]

So my laptop died in this class but it was mostly stuff we already know

Public vs Private fields
Classes can access private fields from other instances as long as its the same class
Static methods can be accessed without creating an instance
Use getter and setter methods, never interface directly with the fields - make fields private and getter/setter methods public
